> Great job on prepping ahead! We can certainly ensure that your filling stays moist. Here's how I suggest you proceed:
> 
> Since your crust is already baked, we need to guard it from burning or over-browning while the filling heats up. One way to help with this is to cover the edges with a pie shield or strips of aluminum foil. The center of the tart will still be exposed and will warm nicely in the oven.
> 
> For the filling, although the recipe doesn't call for baking it after placing it in the tart, that doesn't mean you can't. A brief time in the oven can help meld the flavors and heat everything evenly. To prevent it from drying out:
> 
> 1. Preheat your oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit (175 degrees Celsius).
>    
> 2. Spread your filling in the pre-baked tart shell.
>    
> 3. Cover it with a piece of parchment paper or loosely with foil to prevent the filling from drying out.
> 
> 4. Bake it for about 10-15 minutes, or until the filling is heated through.
> 
> For the extra pie crust you have:
> 
> 1. You could roll it flat, cut out some decorative shapes with a knife (leaves, hearts, etc.), and bake these at 350 degrees Fahrenheit (175 degrees Celsius) until they're golden brown.
>    
> 2. Once they're done, place them on top of your tart as decoration.
>    
> 3. You could also sprinkle these pieces with a bit of sugar before baking for an extra crunch and sweetness.
> 
> For the glaze:
> 
> 1. Melt your pre-made glaze in a small saucepan or in the microwave until it turns into a liquid again.
> 
> 2. Brush the glaze over the warm tart right after it comes out of the oven.
> 
> Finally, let the tart cool for a few minutes before serving. The quick warming in the oven will help the flavors to meld, and the protective covering should prevent your filling from drying out.
> 
> Enjoy your delicious apple-pear tart!
